notesStmt.note: Title supplied by cataloger, based on spine title: Chronicle of England.
First line: Here may a man heren how Englonde was Fyrst called Albyon and thrugh whom it hadde the name.
foliation in pencil; paginated p. 1-168, 172-178, continued in later hand p. 180, 181-186

msContents.summary: History of England from the beginnings up through King Henry V's conquest of Rouen in 1419, and including the stories of King Lear, King Arthur, and other sources for later literature.

msItem.title: Chronicle of England, known as The Brut manuscript, ca. 1440.

respStmt.persName: Folger, Emily C. J. (Emily Clara Jordan), 1858-1936, former owner.

msItem.title: [Chronicles of England]
msItem.incipit: Here may a man heren how Englonde was Fyrst called Albyon and thrugh whom it hadde the name ... [f. 1r]

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 2 columns of 42-50 lines approximately (dimensions of written space: 255 x 190 approximately); frame-ruled in drypoint; writing begins below first line; chapter headings, paraphs, boxes enclosing scribal notes, in red; signs of trimming; some marginalia, pen trials, and other notes in 16th and 17th century hands; a list of the 168 chapter headings at end of volume, made in 1604.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in Secretary hand by one or two scribes.

decoDesc.decoNote: 2-4 line unfilled spaces for initials, sometimes with guide letters.

binding.p: Bound in half-calf with marble paper boards in England ca. 1820.

history.provenance: Formerly owned by Craven Ord (bookplate); Ord sale (London, June 25, 1829, no. 522) to Thorpe for Phillipps; Phillipps sale (London, 1913, no. 1102) to P.M. Barnard; no. 658 in a sale.
